<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-27T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="425" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">662.6331/63: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Austria</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Stockton</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-27T17:00:00-05:00">March 27, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>12. Legation’s 21. March 26, 5 p.m. To date we are without a text of the
                            agreement on the proposed customs union. The statement in the <hi rend="italic">Presse</hi> attributed to the Commerce Department is
                            denied here by the responsible officials. Moreover, we are not seeking
                            explanations either from Germany or Austria. Under these circumstances,
                            if the Austrian Government raises the question, you may, at your
                            discretion, informally review the situation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>